Name: itemStyle

Type: property

Syntax: get the itemStyle[<name>] of <toolbar>
Syntax: set the itemStyle[<name>] of <toolbar> to <style>

Summary:
The visual style of a toolbar item: button, separator, or space.

Associations: toolbar

Introduced: 10.0

OS: mac, windows, linux

Platforms: desktop

Example:
set the itemStyle["divider"] of toolbar 1 to "separator"

Example:
set the itemStyle["gap"] of toolbar 1 to "flexSpace"

Example:
put the itemStyle["saveButton"] of toolbar 1 into tStyle

Value:
The <itemStyle> of a toolbar item is one of the following strings:

- "button" — a standard clickable toolbar button with an optional icon
  and label. This is the default for items created via <itemLabel>.
- "separator" — a non-interactive vertical divider line between groups
  of buttons.
- "space" — a fixed-width empty space between items.
- "flexSpace" — a flexible empty space that expands to fill available
  width, useful for pushing items to the right edge.

Description:
Use the <itemStyle> property to query or change the presentation style
of a named toolbar item.

Separator, space, and flexSpace items do not dispatch
<toolbarItemClicked> messages when clicked and have no meaningful label,
tooltip, icon, or enabled state.

On macOS, separator and space items are rendered using the NSToolbar
system identifiers NSToolbarSeparatorItemIdentifier,
NSToolbarSpaceItemIdentifier, and NSToolbarFlexibleSpaceItemIdentifier.

On Windows, separator items use the TBSTYLE_SEP button style.

On Linux, separators use GtkSeparatorToolItem; space and flexSpace use
GtkSeparatorToolItem with the draw property set to false, and flexSpace
additionally calls gtk_tool_item_set_expand(true).

References: toolbar (object), itemNames (property),
itemLabel (property), itemIcon (property),
toolbarItemClicked (message)

Tags: ui
